    {
      "id": "LUIua8WjtCHaIJOWEUbWG",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1590.2348506545668,
      "y": 472.5004428450101,
      "width": 1360.8719884303127,
      "height": 700,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "b1A",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 1833786999,
      "version": 2261,
      "versionNonce": 478111831,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1784250842099,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Thoughts on this design :\n\n1) This follows the SOLID principles well, at least on surface \n\n2) the DocumentEditor class is calling inheritance on a lot of different classes\n-> Ideally, when creating UML diagrams for LLD stuff we should focus on making sure \nthat most of our design has more COMPOSITION instead of more INHERITANCE\n\n3) This design is better than the previpus design where all the methods were hardcoded into the \nthe DocumentEditor class itself but it still is calling all the methods anyway in that single class even if \nyou can say that the actual logic is in diff classes\n-> This also means that the DocumentEditor class needs to have the knowledge of what methods\nexist in diff classes as it is directly calling them\n-> If we think about this indepth this SORT OF breaks the single responsibility principle\n-> the DocumentEditor class doesnt have more than one reason to change BUT it has more than one way of finding out when it has to\nchange\n--> See the thing is that SOLID principles are, well, principles, they are not LAW, we can only follow principles to a certain EXTENT\n\n4) Basically coming back to the flaw here, its that well if we need to update or delete the render method then we need to change it in\nDocumentElement, Document and DocumentEditor class in all the places\n-> So basically same with the save() method as well, if its updated/deleted it needs to be changed in MULTIPLE places\n--> This is why it SORT OF breaks the single responsibility principle\n\n5) In document class too the same problem / scope for improvement is there that the Document class has knowledge of render() method\n(of whose core logic is being delegated to another class)\nbut still the document class has KNOWLEDGE of another class's method, so it is talking to friend of friend\n\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Thoughts on this design :\n\n1) This follows the SOLID principles well, at least on surface \n\n2) the DocumentEditor class is calling inheritance on a lot of different classes\n-> Ideally, when creating UML diagrams for LLD stuff we should focus on making sure \nthat most of our design has more COMPOSITION instead of more INHERITANCE\n\n3) This design is better than the previpus design where all the methods were hardcoded into the \nthe DocumentEditor class itself but it still is calling all the methods anyway in that single class even if \nyou can say that the actual logic is in diff classes\n-> This also means that the DocumentEditor class needs to have the knowledge of what methods\nexist in diff classes as it is directly calling them\n-> If we think about this indepth this SORT OF breaks the single responsibility principle\n-> the DocumentEditor class doesnt have more than one reason to change BUT it has more than one way of finding out when it has to change\n--> See the thing is that SOLID principles are, well, principles, they are not LAW, we can only follow principles to a certain EXTENT\n\n4) Basically coming back to the flaw here, its that well if we need to update or delete the render method then we need to change it in DocumentElement, Document and DocumentEditor class in all the places\n-> So basically same with the save() method as well, if its updated/deleted it needs to be changed in MULTIPLE places\n--> This is why it SORT OF breaks the single responsibility principle\n\n5) In document class too the same problem / scope for improvement is there that the Document class has knowledge of render() method (of whose core logic is being delegated to another class)\nbut still the document class has KNOWLEDGE of another class's method, so it is talking to friend of friend\n\n",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
